qas.question: What's the name of the public quay that's been in Southampton since the 13th century?
In what decade were the Eastern Docks that can be seen today created?
What company commissioned the program that created the Western Docks?
What body of water was dredged for the material used for reclamation?
In what decade did the Southern Railway Company commission the program that created the Western Docks?

context: <a0_0>Town Quay<a0_0/> is the original public quay, and dates from the 13th century. Today's Eastern Docks were created in the <a1_0>1830s<a1_0/> by land reclamation of the mud flats between the Itchen & Test estuaries. The Western Docks date from the <a4_0>1930s<a4_0/> when the <a2_0>Southern Railway Company<a2_0/> commissioned a major land reclamation and dredging programme. Most of the material used for reclamation came from dredging of <a3_0>Southampton Water<a3_0/>, to ensure that the port can continue to handle large ships.
